\f0\b \cb3 Rape
\f1\b0 \'a0A completed sexual assault by a male, usually upon a female, although sometimes upon another male.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rate of natural increase\'a0
\f1\b0 The difference between birth and death rates, excluding immigration.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rationalization\'a0
\f1\b0 The process of subjecting social relationships to calculation and administration.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Real values\'a0
\f1\b0 The values people consider truly important, as evident in their behavior and how they spend their time and money.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rebellion\'a0
\f1\b0 In anomie theory, a form of deviance that occurs when individuals reject culturally valued means and goals and substitute new means and goals. In political sociology, the expression of opposition to an established authority.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Reference group\'a0
\f1\b0 A social group whose standards and opinions are used by an individual to help define or evaluate beliefs, values, and behaviors.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Reform movement\'a0
\f1\b0 A type of social movement that accepts the status quo but seeks certain specific social reforms.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Regressive movement\'a0
\f1\b0 A type of social movement whose aim is to move the social world back to where members believe it was at an earlier time.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Relative poverty\'a0
\f1\b0 The condition of having much less income than the average person in society, even if one can afford the necessities of life.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Religion\'a0
\f1\b0 A set of shared beliefs and rituals common to a special community and focusing on the sacred and supernatural.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Religious movement\'a0
\f1\b0 An organized religious group with the primary goal of changing existing religious institutions.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Research and development\'a0
\f1\b0 (R&D) Investments in basic research and in the practical application of basic research discoveries.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Research design\'a0
\f1\b0 The specific plan for conducting a research study, including sampling, measurement, and data analysis.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Resocialization\'a0
\f1\b0 The process of socializing people away from a group or activity in which they are involved.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Resource mobilization theory\'a0
\f1\b0 The theory that social movements are affected by their ability to marshal various key resources.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Retreatism\'a0
\f1\b0 In anomie theory, a form of deviance that occurs when individuals abandon culturally valued means and goals.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Revolution\'a0
\f1\b0 A large-scale change in the political leadership of a society and the restructuring of major features of that society.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Revolutionary movement\'a0
\f1\b0 A type of social movement whose aim is to reorganize existing society completely.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Riot\'a0
\f1\b0 A destructive and sometimes violent collective outburst.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rising expectations\'a0
\f1\b0 A situation in which people feel that past hardships should not have to be suffered in the future.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Ritual\'a0
\f1\b0 In the sociology of religion, the rules of conduct concerning behavior in the presence of the sacred. Intended to produce feelings of reverence, awe, and group identity.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Ritualism\'a0
\f1\b0 In anomie theory, a form of deviance in which individuals lose sight of socially valued goals but conform closely to socially prescribed means.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rival hypothesis\'a0
\f1\b0 An explanation that competes with the original hypothesis in a study.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role\'a0
\f1\b0 To functionalists, the culturally prescribed and socially patterned behaviors associated with particular social positions. For interactionists, the effort to mesh the demands of a social position with one's own identity.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role accumulation
\f1\b0 \'a0Adding more statuses and roles to the ones an individual already has.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role conflict\'a0
\f1\b0 A situation in which two or more social roles make incompatible demands on a person.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role exit\'a0
\f1\b0 The process of leaving a role that is central to one's identity and building an identity in a new role while also taking into account one's prior role.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role expectations\'a0
\f1\b0 Commonly shared norms about how a person is supposed to behave in a particular role.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role performance\'a0
\f1\b0 The behaviors of a person performing a certain social role.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Role set\'a0
\f1\b0 The cluster of roles that accompanies a particular status.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rowdyism\'a0
\f1\b0 Generalized interpersonal violence or property destruction occurring at spectator events.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Ruling class\'a0
\f1\b0 A small class that controls the means of economic production and dominates political decisions.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Rumor\'a0
\f1\b0 A report that is passed informally from one person to another without firm evidence.\cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 Sample survey\'a0
\f1\b0 A systematic method of collecting information from respondents, using personal interviews or written questionnaires.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sanction\'a0
\f1\b0 A social reward or punishment for approved or disapproved behavior; can be positive or negative, formal or informal.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Scapegoating\'a0
\f1\b0 Blaming a convenient but innocent person or group for one's trouble or guilt.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Schooling\'a0
\f1\b0 Formal education.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Science\'a0
\f1\b0 An approach used to obtain reliable knowledge about the physical and social worlds, based on systematic empirical observations; the knowledge so obtained.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Scientific productivity\'a0
\f1\b0 Making new discoveries, confirming or disconfirming theoretical hypotheses through experimentation and other types of research, and publishing the results of that research.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Scientific revolution\'a0
\f1\b0 The dramatic overthrow of one intellectual paradigm by another.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Secondary deviance\'a0
\f1\b0 Behavior discovered by others and publicly labeled by them as deviant.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Secondary economic sector\'a0
\f1\b0 The sector of an economy in which raw materials are turned into manufactured goods.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Secondary group\'a0
\f1\b0 A social group bound together for the accomplishment of common tasks, with few emotional ties among members.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sect\'a0
\f1\b0 An exclusive, highly cohesive group of ascetic religious believers. Sects usually last longer and are more institutionalized than cults.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sector theory\'a0
\f1\b0 A theory of urban development explaining that cities develop in wedge-shaped patterns following transportation systems.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Secularization\'a0
\f1\b0 The erosion of belief in the supernatural. Includes a growing respect for rationality, cultural and religious pluralism, tolerance of moral ambiguity, faith in education, and belief in civil rights, the rule of law, and due process.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Self-fulfilling prophecy\'a0
\f1\b0 A belief or prediction about a person or situation that influences that person or situation in such a way that the belief or prediction comes true.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sex\'a0
\f1\b0 The biological distinction of being male or female.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sibling\'a0
\f1\b0 A brother or sister.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social categories\'a0
\f1\b0 Groups of people who may not interact but who share certain social characteristics or statuses.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social change\'a0
\f1\b0 A modification or transformation in the way society is organized.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social class\'a0
\f1\b0 A group's position in a social hierarchy based on prestige and/or property ownership.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social construction of reality\'a0
\f1\b0 The process of socially creating definitions of situations so that they appear to be natural.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social control\'a0
\f1\b0 The relatively patterned and systematic ways in which society guides and restrains individual behaviors so that people act in predictable and desirable ways.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social forces\'a0
\f1\b0 The social structures and culture individuals face in a society.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social inequality\'a0
\f1\b0 The existence of unequal opportunities or rewards for people in different social positions.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social interaction\'a0
\f1\b0 The ways people behave in relation to one another by means of language, gestures, and symbols.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Socialist societies\'a0
\f1\b0 Societies in which productive resources are owned and controlled by the state rather than by individuals.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Socialization\'a0
\f1\b0 The process of preparing newcomers to become members of an existing social group by helping them to learn the attitudes and behaviors that are considered appropriate.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social learning theory\'a0
\f1\b0 A form of learning theory suggesting that people learn through observation and imitation, even though they are not rewarded or punished for certain behaviors.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social mobility\'a0
\f1\b0 The movement from one status to another within a stratified society.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social movement\'a0
\f1\b0 A group of people who work together to guide or suppress particular changes in the way society is organized.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social network\'a0
\f1\b0 A set of interdependent relations or links between individuals.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social psychology\'a0
\f1\b0 The scientific study of how individual behavior is socially influenced.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social relations of production\'a0
\f1\b0 The organization of economic life on the basis of owning or not owning the means of production, purchasing or selling labor power, and controlling or not controlling other people's labor power.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social sciences
\f1\b0 \'a0Disciplines related to sociology that study human activity and communication, including psychology, anthropology, economics, political science.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social stratification\'a0
\f1\b0 The fairly permanent ranking of positions in a society in terms of unequal power, prestige, or privilege.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Social structure
\f1\b0 \'a0Recurrent and patterned relationships among individuals, organizations, nations, or other social units.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Society\'a0
\f1\b0 A group of people with a shared and somewhat distinct culture who live in a defined territory, feel some unity as a group, and see themselves as distinct from other peoples.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sociobiology\'a0
\f1\b0 The scientific study of the biological basis for human behavior.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Socioeconomic status (SES)\'a0
\f1\b0 An index of social status that considers a person's occupation, education, and income as measures of social status.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sociology\'a0
\f1\b0 The study and analysis of patterned social relationships in modern societies.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sovereignty\'a0
\f1\b0 The authority claimed by a state to maintain a legal system, use coercive power to secure obedience, and maintain its independence from other states.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sponsored mobility\'a0
\f1\b0 A pattern in which certain children are selected at an early age for academic and university education and are thus helped to achieve higher social status.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sport\'a0
\f1\b0 A form of game in which the outcome is affected by physical skill.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Staff job\'a0
\f1\b0 In an organization, an advisory or administrative job that supports the manufacturing, production, selling, or other primary activities of the organization.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Stage theory\'a0
\f1\b0 A theory suggesting that nations go through various systematic stages of development.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 State\'a0
\f1\b0 The institutionalized, legal organization of power within territorial limits.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 State sector\'a0
\f1\b0 The sector of the economy controlled by local, state, or federal governments that supplies goods and services under direct contract to that state.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 State terrorism\'a0
\f1\b0 The use of torture, death squads, and disappearances by political states to intimidate citizens.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Status\'a0
\f1\b0 A socially defined position in society that carries with it certain prescribed rights, obligations, and expected behaviors.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Status-attainment model\'a0
\f1\b0 A view of social mobility suggesting the importance of father's education, father's occupation, son's education, and son's first job for a man's adult status. (Early research was based only on men.)\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Status group\'a0
\f1\b0 People who share a social identity based on similar values and life-styles.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Status inconsistency\'a0
\f1\b0 May occur when an individual occupies two or more unequal statuses in a society.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Stigmatization\'a0
\f1\b0 The process of spoiling a person's identity by labeling him or her in a negative way.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Structural change\'a0
\f1\b0 Demographic, economic, and rank-order changes in a society.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Structural-functional perspective\'a0
\f1\b0 One of the major theoretical perspectives in sociology, developed by Talcott Parsons: focuses on how the various parts of society fit together or adjust to maintain the equilibrium of the whole.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Subculture\'a0
\f1\b0 A distinguishable group that shares a number of features with the dominant culture within which it exists while also having unique features such as language, customs, or values.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Subjective meanings\'a0
\f1\b0 The values and interpretations individuals place on their life situations and experiences; may vary from person to person.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Subjective social class\'a0
\f1\b0 A person's own perception of his or her class position.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Suburb\'a0
\f1\b0 A fairly small community within an urban area that includes a central city.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Sunbelt\'a0
\f1\b0 The area south of the 37th parallel in the United States, including Clark County in Nevada.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Superego\'a0
\f1\b0 In Freudian theory, the part of the personality structure that upholds the norms of society.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Symbol\'a0
\f1\b0 Any object or sign that evokes a shared social response.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Symbolic interaction\'a0
\f1\b0 Interaction that relies on shared symbols such as language.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Symbolic interactionism\'a0
\f1\b0 An interpretive perspective, inspired by the work of George Herbert Mead, saying that individuals learn meanings through interaction with others and then organize their lives around these socially created meanings.\cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 Taboo\'a0
\f1\b0 A strongly prohibited social practice; the strongest form of social norm.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Technological determinism\'a0
\f1\b0 The belief that technological development shapes social life in rather fixed ways.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Technology\'a0
\f1\b0 The practical applications of scientific knowledge.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Tension release theory\'a0
\f1\b0 A theory suggesting that sport serves as a form of social safety valve, allowing individuals to vent their seething aggressions.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Terrorism\'a0
\f1\b0 An attack on people designed to frighten society and force it to meet the terrorists' demands.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Tertiary economic sector\'a0
\f1\b0 The sector of an economy that offers services to individuals as well as to business.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Theoretical approach\'a0
\f1\b0 A set of guiding ideas.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Theory\'a0
\f1\b0 A system of orienting ideas, concepts, and relationships that provides a way of organizing the observable world.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Theory\'a0
\f1\b0 X A view of organizational behavior suggesting that people hate their jobs, want to avoid responsibility, resist change, and do not care about organizational needs.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Theory\'a0
\f1\b0 Y A view of organizational behavior suggesting that people have the desire to work, to be creative, and to take responsibility for their jobs and for the organization.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Theory\'a0
\f1\b0 Z A form of organizational culture that values long-term employment, trust, and close personal relationships between workers and managers.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Total fertility rate\'a0
\f1\b0 An estimate of the average number of children that would be born to each woman over her reproductive life if current age-specific birth rates remained constant.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Total institution\'a0
\f1\b0 A place where people spend 24 hours of every day for an extended part of their lives, cut off from the rest of society and tightly controlled by the people in charge.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Totalitarianism\'a0
\f1\b0 A form of autocracy that involves the use of state power to control and regulate all phases of life.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Tournament selection\'a0
\f1\b0 An educational pattern in which a continual process of selection serves to weed out candidates; winners move on to the next round of selection and losers are eliminated from the competition.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Tracking\'a0
\f1\b0 The practice of grouping students by ability, curriculum, or both.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Triad\'a0
\f1\b0 A group composed of three people.\cb1 \
