\f0\b \cf2 Underemployment\'a0
\f1\b0 The hiring of people in jobs that are not customarily filled by individuals with their relatively high levels of experience or education.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Underground economy\'a0
\f1\b0 Exchanges of goods and services that occur outside the arena of the normal, regulated economy and therefore escape official record keeping.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Unit of analysis\'a0
\f1\b0 Who or what is being studied in a piece of social research.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Urbanization\'a0
\f1\b0 The growth of cities.\cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 Value-added theory\'a0
\f1\b0 A theory suggesting that many instances of collective behavior represent efforts to change the social environment.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Values\'a0
\f1\b0 Strongly held general ideas that people share about what is good and bad, desirable or undesirable; values provide yardsticks for judging specific acts and goals.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Variable\'a0
\f1\b0 A logical set of attributes with different degrees of magnitude or different categories. For example, age is a variable on which people can be classified according to the number of years they have lived.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Verstehen\'a0
\f1\b0 The effort to understand social behavior in terms of the motives individuals bring to it.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Vertical integration\'a0
\f1\b0 A form of business organization that attempts to control the business environment by assuming control of one or more of its resources or business outlets.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Vertical mobility\'a0
\f1\b0 Movement of an individual or a group upward or downward, from one social status to another.\cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 Wealth\'a0
\f1\b0 The total value (minus debts) of what is owned.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 Weberian approach\'a0
\f1\b0 The views held by conflict theorists who, using the ideas of Max Weber, stress the significance of conflict in social life, especially conflict among status groups such as those based on occupation, ethnic background, or religion.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 White-collar crime\'a0
\f1\b0 Crimes committed by "respectable" individuals, often while they practice their occupations-- for example, embezzling money or stealing computer time.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 White ethnics\'a0
\f1\b0 White Americans who value and preserve aspects of their ethnic heritage.\cb1 \

\f0\b \cb3 World systems analysis\'a0
\f1\b0 A form of sociological analysis that stresses understanding national behavior in terms of historical and contemporary relationships among nations and societies .\cb1 \
\

\f0\b \cb3 Zero population growth (ZPG)\'a0
\f1\b0 The situation that occurs when the population of a nation or the world remains stable from one year to the next.\
